---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

const title = "Audio Formats Explained: MP3 vs AAC vs M4A";
const description = "Understand the difference between MP3, AAC, and M4A containers. Which audio format offers the best quality for your downloads?";
const publishDate = new Date('2026-01-05').toISOString();
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <Header />
  
  <main class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-200 min-h-screen pt-32 pb-20 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-invert prose-violet">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-black text-transparent bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-r from-violet-400 to-fuchsia-400 mb-8">{title}</h1>
      
      <p class="lead text-xl text-slate-300 mb-8">
        When converting videos, you are often faced with a choice: MP3 or MP4? And what about AAC? This guide breaks down the alphabet soup of audio codecs.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">MP3 (MPEG-1 Audio Layer III)</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>The Universal Standard.</strong> MP3 is the most compatible audio format in history. It plays on literally everythingâ€”from 20-year-old car stereos to modern smartwatches.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-slate-400">
        <li><strong>Pros</strong>: 100% Compatibility, ID3 Tag support (Cover Art, Artist Name).</li>
        <li><strong>Cons</strong>: Older compression technology. Needs higher bitrates (320kbps) to match the quality of newer formats at lower sizes.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">AAC (Advanced Audio Coding) / M4A</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>The Modern Successor.</strong> Often wrapped in an <code>.m4a</code> container, AAC is the standard for YouTube streaming and Apple devices.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-slate-400">
        <li><strong>Pros</strong>: Better sound quality than MP3 at the same bitrate. 192kbps AAC roughly equals 320kbps MP3.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons</strong>: Slightly less compatibility with very old hardware.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Which Should You Choose?</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
        <div class="bg-violet-600/20 p-6 rounded-xl border border-violet-500/30">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-violet-300 mt-0">Choose MP3 If:</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">You need to play the file on a wide variety of devices (car stereo, old MP3 player, gaming console) and want maximum compatibility.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-sky-600/20 p-6 rounded-xl border border-sky-500/30">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-sky-300 mt-0">Choose MP4/AAC If:</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">You want the absolute best quality-to-size ratio and are primarily playback on smartphones or modern computers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8">
        Convert2MP3 optimizes for <strong>MP3</strong> by default because compatibility is usually the #1 priority for our users, ensuring your music works everywhere.
      </p>

      <!-- Article Schema -->
      <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Article",
        "headline": title,
        "image": [
            "https://convert2mp3.online/og-image.jpg"
        ],
        "datePublished": publishDate,
        "author": [{
            "@type": "Organization",
            "name": "Convert2MP3 Team",
            "url": "https://convert2mp3.online"
        }]
      })} />
    </article>
  </main>
  
  <Footer />
</Layout>
